english:
  title: A Memorial to the Chancellor of the Central Secretariat at the Capital
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the first month of the third year of Zhizhi, the various officials of Goryeo's Office of Remonstrance humbly purify ourselves and present this memorial with a hundred bows to the Chancellor and Ministers of the Central Secretariat.

    When matters are about to sprout, to speak against them borders on madness. When feelings are bottled up and difficult to express, silence borders on concealment. If we must choose, let us err toward madness rather than silence. We humbly beg that you regard our directness with generous compassion.

    The Mean teaches: "In governing the realm and the state, there are nine great principles, yet the essence of practicing them is but one—sincerity." To continue broken lines of descent, to restore fallen kingdoms, to order chaos and steady the trembling—this is done by being generous to those who came before and frugal with those who come after, so as to embrace the lords. As the sage says: "Continue those without heirs; enfeoff those already destroyed. Let upper and lower be at ease with each other; let great and small care for one another. Then all under heaven will exhaust their loyalty and strength in protecting the royal house."

    In ancient times, Duke Huan of Qi relocated the people of Xing as though they were returning home, and enfeoffed Wei so they forgot their ruin. Thus he unified the realm and became first among the Five Hegemons. If even a hegemon knew to attend to such matters, how much more so should one who dwells in the center of all lands and calls the four seas his home?

    We humbly reflect that our small kingdom, founded by our ancestor Wang, has endured for over four hundred years. We have served the great dynasty with loyal tribute these hundred and more years. In the year of Wuyin, there was a bandit calling himself the Prince of Jinshan, scion of the Liao house, who plundered the people of the central plains and invaded our eastern islands, raging without restraint. The Great Ancestor, the Sagely Martial Emperor, dispatched two generals to vanquish this scourge. When heavy snows cut off supplies, our loyal king commanded his ministers to provision the army, and the bandits were destroyed as swiftly as bamboo splits. The two generals and our ministers swore brotherhood, their oath to endure ten thousand generations.

    Again in the year of Jiwei, when the World-Founder Emperor led his armies south, our king, perceiving the will of heaven and the people's accord, traveled over six thousand li to meet him at Bianliang. Our loyalty was thus rewarded: we received imperial princesses and became imperial relatives generation after generation, yet preserved our ancient customs and protected our ancestral temples. This was possible only through the imperial decree of the World-Founder.

    When establishing provinces throughout the realm, he alone excluded our small kingdom. Later, though military campaigns against Japan gave nominal justification, such measures were never rigorously applied. In the Great Virtue era, when an official was appointed to be the eyes and ears of the throne, he memorialized that our nation had received the sacred edict not to alter its ancient ways, only to change official titles. The Enlightened Emperor affirmed this petition, and the official returned. The Benevolent Emperor in his rescript explicitly forbade any to petition otherwise regarding Goryeo's lands.

    Now we hear the court wishes to establish a provincial administration over our kingdom like the other regions. If this is true, what becomes of the World-Founder's decree? What of the compassion of successive emperors? We have read the recent edict of the eleventh month, calling upon right and wrong to take different paths, so as to restore peace to all lands and recover the governance of the Zhongtong and Zhiyuan eras. This pronouncement is indeed a blessing to all under heaven.

    Given that our nation has served through successive dynasties with loyalty as theirs, and given the deep compassion of the emperors, to suddenly abolish four hundred years of established order would be most injurious. What of other foreign lands with no such service? How would the court justify treating them? How would this accord with the original principle of that governance?

    Consider: our realm spans no more than a thousand li. Seven of every ten parts are barren mountain and forest. Taxes from such land cannot meet transport costs; revenues from our people cannot cover their own salaries. We are but a speck of dust upon Taishan in serving the nation's needs. Our land is distant, our people simple, our speech unlike the Middle Kingdom's, our customs divergent from those of Cathay. Should they hear of such changes, suspicion and fear would take root. Nor could any proclamation quickly dispel it. Moreover, our land faces the Japanese across the sea. Should they learn of this, might they not take warning from our fate and reconsider their own submission?

    We humbly beseech you: embody the court's regard for past service; remember the teachings of the Mean. Let the kingdom remain itself and its people remain theirs. Let them perfect their governance as a barrier protecting your endless peace. Then not only will the people of the three Han celebrate in joy and sing of your virtue, but the spirits of our ancestral temples will weep in gratitude in the realm beyond.

    We await your illumination with hearts full of urgent entreaty and reverent petition. Forgive us for soiling your majesty. We kowtow a hundred times.
